Think of a loan as a story with 3 acts:
Act 1 — Birth of the loan

A borrower needs money. The lender checks their credit score and FOIR (can they afford it?), agrees on the principal, interest rate, and tenure, and on the disbursal date, the money lands in the borrower's account. From this day, the clock starts ticking.
Act 2 — The repayment journey

Every month, on the due date, the borrower pays an EMI via NACH auto-debit. Each payment is logged: was it on time? Late by how many days (DPD)? If they go past 1–90 DPD, they fall into delinquency buckets — think of it like a traffic light going from yellow to red. The collections team steps in at various stages to recover the money.
Act 3 — Resolution (one of 4 ways)

✅ Normal closure — all EMIs paid, NOC issued, done.
⚡ Foreclosure — borrower pays off early.
⚠️ Settlement — borrower pays partial amount, lender absorbs some loss.
❌ Write-off — lender gives up recovering, books the loss. Borrower's credit is destroyed.

The key insight — everything in this domain ultimately revolves around one number: DPD. It drives delinquency buckets, NPA classification, provisioning, collections intensity, and recovery strategy. Once you understand DPD, everything else connects naturally.
